  "prompt": "How do I solve [math]\\displaystyle\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3}+x)[/math]?",
  "response": "To evaluate the limit \\(\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3}+x)\\), we start by simplifying the expression inside the limit.\n\nWe have:\n\\[\ny = \\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x.\n\\]\n\nRewriting the expression inside the cube root:\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3 (1 - \\frac{x^2}{x^3})} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3 (1 - \\frac{1}{x})}.\n\\]\nWe can simplify this further:\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{-x^3 (1 - \\frac{1}{x})} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3} \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}}.\n\\]\n\nThe cube root of \\(-x^3\\) is:\n\\[\n-x.\n\\]\nThus, the expression becomes:\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = -x \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}}.\n\\]\n\nApproximating \\(\\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}}\\):\nFor large \\(x\\), \\(\\frac{1}{x}\\) is small, and we can use the binomial expansion:\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} \\approx 1 - \\frac{1}{3x}.\n\\]\n\nThus:\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} \\approx -x \\cdot \\left(1 - \\frac{1}{3x}\\right) = -x + \\frac{x}{3}.\n\\]\n\nAdding \\(x\\) to it, the effective expression for \\(y\\) is:\n\\[\ny \\approx \\left(-x + \\frac{x}{3}\\right) + x.\n\\]\nSimplifying:\n\\[\ny \\approx -x + \\frac{x}{3} + x = \\frac{x}{3}.\n\\]\n\nAs \\(x \\to \\infty\\), \\(y \\to \\frac{x}{3} - \\frac{x}{3} = -\\infty\\).\n\nTherefore, the limit is:\n\\[\n\\lim_{x \\to \\infty} (\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x) = -\\infty.\n\\]",
